@Sumi-Sumi If you do not use SELinux then do not use a SELinux label aka context `nvidia_container_t` 
`--security-opt label=type:nvidia_container_t` this is SELinux related. 

Try to run without the `security-opt` if it still fails try privileged if this succeeds we may have wrong privs on the device files.  You can also try to run the container with `/bin/bash`  and do a `ls -Zla /dev/nvidia*`. A CUDA application will try to allocate memory and will access more files and devices. A nvidia-smi is on the "driver" level where Pytorch is a runtime app.
